problem: Julie works for 48 hours per week for 12 weeks during the summer, making $\$5000$. If she works for 48 weeks during the school year at the same rate of pay and needs to make another $\$5000$, how many hours per week must she work?
solution: Since she only needs to make the same amount of money, if she works for 4 times as many weeks, she can work 4 times fewer hours per week, meaning she can work $\frac{1}{4} \cdot 48 = \boxed{12}$ hours per week.
model_solution:
Step 1: Let $h$ be the rate of pay per hour.
$\frac{48 \text{ hours}}{1 \text{ week}} \times 12 \text{ weeks} \times \frac{\$5000}{48 \times 12} = h$
Step 2: $h=\frac{\$5000}{576}$
Step 3: $\frac{576}{48}h=\frac{576}{48}\left(\frac{\$5000}{576}\right)$
Step 4: $12h=\frac{12 \times \$5000}{576}$
$\frac{12 \times \$5000}{576}=\$25$
Step 5: $\frac{\$5000}{12h}=\frac{\$5000}{12\left(\frac{\$5000}{576}\right)}$
$\frac{\$5000}{12\left(\frac{\$5000}{576}\right)}=\frac{576}{12}$
$\frac{576}{12}=48$
Step 6: $48 \text{ weeks} \times \frac{\$5000}{48 \text{ weeks}} = h \times 48$
Step 7: $\frac{576}{12}h=\frac{576}{12}\left(\frac{\$5000}{48}\right)$
$\frac{576}{12}\left(\frac{\$5000}{48}\right) = \$100$
